Methodology
Data preparation

Loaded two datasets: (i) daily crypto Fear & Greed Index (fear_greed_index.csv), (ii) detailed trade history (historical_data.csv).

Checked missing values and duplicates; both datasets had no NaNs and no duplicate rows.

Parsed dates:

Sentiment: date converted to datetime, classification renamed to sentiment.

Trades: Timestamp IST parsed to datetime, and a date column extracted for daily aggregation.

Feature engineering

Trade-level flags:

is_win = Closed PnL > 0

is_long if Side ∈ {Long, Buy}, otherwise inferred as short.

Daily per‑trader metrics via groupby(['date','Account']):

daily_pnl (sum of Closed PnL)

n_trades (count of trades)

win_rate (mean of is_win)

avg_trade_size (mean Size Tokens)

avg_leverage (approximated using Size USD as a proxy for trade value)

long_ratio (share of long trades).

Daily market‑level metrics aggregated across traders per day: total PnL, average PnL per trade, total number of trades, average leverage, and long ratio.

Sentiment merge & segmentation

Merged daily trading metrics with the daily Fear & Greed sentiment by date.

Sentiment distribution after merge: Greed (193 days), Extreme Greed (114), Fear (91), Neutral (67), Extreme Fear (14), with one NaN sentiment day.

Built sentiment‑conditioned summaries of:

Mean and median total daily PnL, mean PnL per trade, and number of days per sentiment bucket.

Minimum cumulative PnL trajectory per sentiment class to assess drawdown behavior.

Average trades/day, average leverage, and long ratio by sentiment.

Further split days into high‑ vs low‑leverage segments (based on distribution of daily average Size USD) within each sentiment to study interaction between sentiment and leverage.

Key Insights
PnL vs sentiment

Mean daily total PnL is highest in Extreme Fear (~52.8k) and Fear (~36.9k), while Greed shows the lowest mean (~11.1k).

Median daily PnL confirms this skew: Extreme Fear has the highest typical day (~22.6k), Extreme Greed and Fear are clearly positive, and Greed days have relatively small median gains (~0.7k).

Mean PnL per trade is also strong in Neutral (~63.8) and Extreme Greed (~56.7), suggesting that trade quality (profit per execution) is better when sentiment is balanced or very optimistic, while raw PnL volume is largest in fearful regimes.

Risk and drawdowns

The minimum cumulative PnL by sentiment bucket is worst for Fear (~256k) and Neutral (~252.6k), somewhat better for Extreme Fear (~265.9k) and Greed (~139.2k), and lowest for Extreme Greed (~102.4k). (Higher value = less severe drawdown, assuming cumulative PnL scale.)

This suggests fearful and neutral regimes can host both very profitable and very stressful periods, while Extreme Greed tends to show smaller net drawdowns over the analyzed horizon.

Volume, positioning, and leverage

Average trades/day: highest under Extreme Fear (~1,529 trades/day), followed by Fear (~680) and Neutral (~562); Greed and Extreme Greed see far fewer trades (≈261 and 351).

Average daily leverage proxy (Size USD) rises from Extreme Fear (~4.1k) to Extreme Greed (~4.4k) and peaks under Neutral (~7.2k), suggesting traders size up in more “comfortable” environments.

Long/short balance (long ratio) is close to 0.5 across all sentiment buckets (≈0.46–0.51), indicating no strong bias toward longs or shorts purely from the Fear & Greed label.

Leverage–sentiment interaction

Within each sentiment bucket, high‑leverage days consistently have much higher mean daily PnL than low‑leverage days (e.g., under Extreme Fear, ~8.4k vs ~60; under Neutral, ~6.4k vs ~0.8k).

However, high‑leverage days also tend to have higher win rates (≈0.35–0.39) but with fewer trades per day in some regimes, suggesting selective but aggressive risk‑taking is what drives the gains.

Low‑leverage days show lower win rates (~0.27–0.38) and often more trades, implying more “grinding” with smaller edge.

Strategy Recommendations
Exploit fearful regimes with controlled aggression

Since Extreme Fear and Fear days deliver the highest mean daily PnL, consider increasing exposure (position size/number of setups) during these periods, but constrain risk via hard max drawdown limits and per‑trade loss caps to handle the higher volatility suggested by drawdown stats.

Avoid over‑trading in “Greed” conditions

Greed days show the weakest profitability despite moderate leverage and activity.

Implement rules that tighten entry criteria and reduce trade frequency when sentiment is “Greed” (but not Extreme), focusing only on high‑conviction setups and avoiding FOMO‑driven trades.

Leverage sizing framework tied to sentiment

Use a dynamic leverage schedule:

Slightly higher allowable leverage and more capital allocation in Extreme Fear, Fear, and Neutral (where PnL per trade or total PnL is strongest).

More conservative leverage caps in plain Greed and possibly in Extreme Greed when signals are noisy.

Combine sentiment with volatility filters (e.g., realized vol or ATR) before scaling up positions to avoid oversized risk on exceptionally volatile days.

Focus on trade quality, not only trade count

PnL per trade is high in Neutral and Extreme Greed, suggesting quality over quantity performs best there.

Add KPI monitoring of avg PnL per trade by sentiment regime, and enforce a rule to cut daily activity once average PnL per trade degrades below a threshold for that sentiment state.

Portfolio/risk management overlay

Use sentiment as a regime flag in your risk engine:

Adjust daily loss limits, maximum open risk, and number of concurrent positions by sentiment bucket.

Track performance of each trader (or strategy) by sentiment to specialize allocation to those who outperform in specific regimes (e.g., volatility hunters in Fear, mean‑reversion specialists in Neutral).
